In the realm of public criticism, an Indian guru who took up martial arts at age 50, [[Swami sukhabodhananda]], has made a point of stating that young women working in call centers (presumably at all hours) could also benefit by learning jujitsu for self-defence.&lt;ref name = &quot;jujitsu&quot;&gt;[http://www.hinduonnet.com/2006/01/13/stories/2006011319700200.htm From management to martial arts], by Govind D. Belgaumkar. The Hindu, Jan 13, 2006&lt;/ref&gt;

== Outsourced bureau contact centres ==
Outsourced bureau contact centres are a model of contact centre that provide services on a &quot;pay per use&quot; model. The overheads of the contact centre are shared by many clients thereby supporting a very cost effecive model especially for low volumes of calls.

Bureau contact centres provide an opportunity for:
* Pilot schemes - perform test of concept for new models for communications, sales or customer services before investing in staff and infrastructure
* Flexible solutions for SME's - small or medium-size enterprises can benefit from a flexible service that can evolve with the businss
* Best of breed systems/technology - clients can benefit from considerable investment into communications technology, leveraging benefits without having to invest in large cap-ex projects.

== Unionisation ==
Unions in [[North America]] have made some effort to gain members from this sector,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book  | coauthors = Pradeep Kumar, Christopher Robert Schenk  | title = Paths to Union Renewal  | publisher = Broadview Press  | year=  2006  | isbn = 1-55193-058-7  | author = ed. by Pradeep Kumar ... }}&lt;/ref&gt; including the [[Communications Workers of America]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cwa-union.org/news/entry/Improving_Call_Center_Jobs_a_Top_Priority_for_CWA_Customer_Service_Activist/|title=Improving Call Center Jobs a Top Priority for CWA Customer Service |publisher=Communicattion Workers of America|accessdate=2011-02-23}} &lt;/ref&gt; and the [[United Steelworkers]]. In [[Australia]], the [[National Union of Workers]] represents unionised workers; their activities form part of the Australian labour movement.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://workers.labor.net.au/90/news22_call.html|title=Call Centre Union Busters Get Wake-Up Call|publisher=Workers Online|accessdate=2008-07-08}}&lt;/ref&gt; In [[Europe]], Uni Global Union of [[Switzerland]] is involved in assisting unionisation in this realm.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.uniglobalunion.org/uniindep.nsf/callcentres?openpage|title=Uni Global Union's call centre organising campaigns|publisher=Uni Global Union|accessdate=2008-07-08}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Standardisation ==
Customer Operations Performance Center Inc. (COPC) is the globally recognized performance management framework for the contact center and BPO industry.  You can become certified to the COPC-2000 CSP Standard after demonstrating compliance to over 30 different items of contact center performance as outlined in the COPC-2000 CSP Standard.  Information can be obtained at www.COPC.com.

The COPC-2000 CSP Standard can be downloaded for free and is &quot;open source&quot; meaning it can also be utilized within your contact center as a service to the industry.

== Mathematical theory ==
[[Queueing theory|Queuing theory]] is a branch of mathematics in which [[Queueing model|models of queuing]] systems have been developed. A call centre can be seen as a queuing network.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.vu.nl/~koole/ccmath/book.pdf |title=Call Center Mathematics &amp;#124; A scientific method for understanding and improving contact centers by Ger Koole |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-11-03}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.cs.vu.nl/obp/callcenters/overview.pdf Queueing Models of Call Centers: An Introduction Ger Koole]{{dead link|date=November 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The models can be applied to answer queueing questions for call centres.  The most widespread queueing model used is the [[Erlang unit|Erlang C Formula]].

Call centre operations have been supported by mathematical models beyond queueing, with [[operations research]], which considers a wide range of [[Optimization (mathematics)|optimisation problems]].

