      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Infobox Language family
  |name=Chadic
  |iso5=cdc
  |region=[[Nigeria]], [[Niger]], [[Chad]], [[Central African Republic]], [[Cameroon]]
  |familycolor=Afro-asiatic
  |fam1=[[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic]]
  |child1=[[Biu-Mandara languages|Biu-Mandara]]
  |child2=[[East Chadic languages|East Chadic]]
  |child3=[[Masa languages|Masa]]
  |child4=[[West Chadic languages|West Chadic]]
  |iso5=cdc
}}
The '''Chadic languages''' constitute a language family spoken across northern [[Nigeria]], [[Niger]], [[Chad]], [[Central African Republic]] and [[Cameroon]], belonging to the [[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic phylum]]. The most widely spoken Chadic language is [[Hausa language|Hausa]], a [[lingua franca]] of much of inland West [[Africa]]. 

Newman 1977 divided the family into four groups, which have been accepted in all subsequent literature: 

*[[West Chadic languages]]
:Two branches, which include
::(A) the [[Hausa language|Hausa]], [[Ron languages|Ron]], [[Bole languages|Bole]], and [[Angas languages|Angas]] languages; and
::(B) the [[Bade languages|Bade]], [[Warji language|Warji]], and [[Zaar languages|Zaar]] languages. 
*[[Biu-Mandara languages]] (Central Chadic)
:Three branches, which include
::(A) the [[Bura language|Bura]], [[Kamwe language|Kamwe]], and [[Bata language]]s, among other groups; 
::(B) the [[Buduma language|Buduma]] and [[Musgu language|Musgu]] languages; and
::(C) the [[Gidar language]]
*[[East Chadic languages]]
:Two branches, which include
::(A) the [[Tumak language|Tumak]], [[Nancere language|Nancere]], and [[Kera languages|Kera]] languages; and 
::(B) the [[Dangaléat language|Dangaléat]], [[Mokulu language|Mokulu]], and [[Sokoro language|Sokoro]] languages
*[[Masa languages]]

